Weapons.

A weapon is what the player and armed humans fire. The same weapon file produces the same behavior whether the player draws it or a human picks it up at spawn, so every stat written below applies equally to both wielders.

Each weapon lives in its own folder under a category folder. The four categories that ship by default are archery, artillery, explosive, and melee, but the engine treats whatever folders exist under sounds/main/equipments/weapons/ as valid categories — drop a new folder there (e.g. specials, magic, throwing) and the weapons menu, the /draw slash command, and randomly armed enemies all start using it automatically with no code change. The full file path to a weapon is sounds/main/equipments/weapons/<category>/<weapon>/data/info.sif, with the weapon's audio clips alongside it in sounds/main/equipments/weapons/<category>/<weapon>/general/.

Sound assets and info.sif files.

Weapon stats live in info.sif files under sounds/main/. The full path is sounds/main/equipments/weapons/<category>/<weapon>/data/info.sif.

The paths shown below describe the decompiled (loose folder) form of these files. The game also accepts the compiled pack form of the same content (the global main.spack at sounds/compiled/main.spack), and the lookup order is folders first, packs as fallback, so the two forms can coexist on disk. See the packs help topic for the full explanation of how decompiled folders and compiled packs interact.

Each weapon has its own info.sif. The file is self contained: every stat the weapon uses is written explicitly, and anything left out falls through to a sensible default.

The info.sif file does not list any sounds. The engine learns what audio a weapon has by scanning the weapon's general/ subfolder, matching whatever clips it finds against the names it expects (draw, fire, hit, loop, rico, shell, empty, reload, ping, on, off, ref, block). Drop a clip in general/ and the weapon plays it; remove it and the weapon goes silent for that event. There is nothing to wire up by hand because the folder layout is the audio configuration.

Field reference.

Every field in info.sif uses the form key=value, one per line. Missing fields fall back to the defaults shown below.

damage (int): The weapon's base damage per hit. The wielder's own attack bonus is added on top: the player's flat attack stat in the player's case, the human's effective attack times level in the human's case. The player also adds a per-type damage bonus (damage_<type> from kombat.sif for non-melee, damage_melee for melee), bought through the shop's damage tab. Final damage on a player swing or shot is weapon damage + attack + per-type bonus. Humans skip the per-type bonus entirely, so npc damage is just weapon damage + npc attack. Defaults to 1.

fire mode (int): How the weapon fires. 0 is manual fire, where each press of the fire key triggers one shot, paced by spam time. 1 is auto fire, where holding the fire key triggers a continuous stream, paced by repeat time. Defaults to 0.

melee (bool): Whether the weapon uses melee combat math instead of ranged combat math. true means it swings instead of fires, ignores ammo entirely, and the X key reports this weapon does not take any ammo. false means it consumes loaded ammo per shot, plays the fire clip, and uses range based bullet physics. Defaults to true for weapons in the melee category folder and false for weapons in any other folder, so the field is optional unless you want to override the folder's default — for example, a club authored under specials with melee=true behaves like a melee weapon despite its folder.

scadder (int or int pair): How a swing or bullet impact scatters damage to multiple targets at once. Written as scadder=R for an unlimited-target scatter zone of R tiles, or scadder=R:N to cap the total targets damaged at N (with N=0 or omitted meaning unlimited). Setting scadder=0 (or omitting the field) keeps the weapon at single target — a melee swing hits only the single nearest valid target in range and on your facing side, and a bullet hits only its impact target.

Setting R to a positive number activates the scatter zone. For melee, R is the scatter radius around the player in tiles, but targets must also be within the weapon's normal range box, so a small R constrains scatter to a tighter zone within reach and a large R lets scatter use the full weapon range. For bullets, R is the splash radius around the bullet's impact tile in tiles, no weapon-range constraint since the bullet has already traveled. The N count caps the total targets a single swing or bullet impact can damage, where the primary target the bullet first hit counts as one of the N.
Sixteen entity types take scatter damage: npcs, tts enemies, destructible walls, doors, calendars, clocks, signs, items, spikes, security cameras, parked vehicles, parked aircraft, parked bikes, projectiles, staircases, and platforms. Indestructible variants of those types are skipped. Defaults to 0.

swing speed (int milliseconds): Manual melee swing wind-up — how long after you press fire before the hit actually lands. Defaults to 0, meaning the strike resolves the same frame you press fire (instant hit).
Setting it to a positive value adds a wind-up: pressing fire plays the swing audio and starts a timer, and the actual hit lands swing speed milliseconds later. The strike re-targets at impact time, so the swing follows you if you turn or step during the wind-up — whatever direction you're facing and whichever tile you're standing on when the timer elapses is what decides who takes the hit. While a swing is winding up, pressing fire again does nothing until the strike resolves. Spam time still gates manual fire cadence in parallel, so the weapon is locked between presses for whichever of swing speed and spam time is longer; the difference is that swing speed delays the impact while spam time is recovery after it. Only manual fire (fire mode 0) uses this field; auto fire (fire mode 1) ignores it and keeps firing at repeat time intervals with instant hits.

x range (int): On a non melee weapon, how far in tiles the bullet flies along the x axis before vanishing. On a melee weapon, how far along the x axis the swing can reach to hit a target — the swing's hit box extends from the wielder out by this many tiles in the facing direction, so a sword with x range=3 hits enemies up to three tiles away while x range=1 only hits adjacent tiles. Defaults to 1.
y range (int): The y axis equivalent of x range. Same dual meaning: bullet flight distance for non melee, swing reach for melee. Defaults to 1.
z range (int): The z axis (height) equivalent of x range. Same dual meaning: bullet flight distance for non melee, swing reach for melee. Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored. Defaults to 1.

For non melee weapons the bullet is removed when its x, y, or (on 3d maps) z distance from where it was fired exceeds the matching range, so each range field accurately reflects how far the bullet flies regardless of who fired it. For melee weapons the swing always lands instantly at strike time, so range is purely about which tiles the swing can reach, not how long the strike takes to resolve.

bullet speed (int): How fast the bullet flies through the air, written as milliseconds per tile of travel. Lower values mean a faster bullet. Total flight time from spawn to impact equals bullet speed multiplied by the number of tiles between the firer and the target, so the same weapon takes longer to land a far hit than a near one. Defaults to 30.

Note that bullet speed is not a press cooldown — it does nothing to gate when you can fire again. Spam time and repeat time are the press-rate caps; bullet speed only governs what happens after a bullet leaves the barrel. You can fire several shots in quick succession (limited by spam time) while earlier bullets are still mid-flight, and a slow-bullet weapon happily lets multiple bullets stack in the air at once.

Bullet speed is the ranged analog of swing speed in that both delay the moment of impact, but with different mechanics. Swing speed is a fixed wind-up — hit lands at press-time plus swing speed regardless of target distance. Bullet speed is a per-tile travel rate — hit lands when the bullet finally reaches the target, which scales with how far away the target is. A bullet weapon is also unlike a melee swing in that the bullet can miss if the target moves out of the path mid-flight or if the bullet runs out of range first; a melee swing always lands wherever the firer is aimed at strike time.

repeat time (int): Auto fire recovery in milliseconds. While fire mode is 1, the weapon will not fire again until repeat time has elapsed since the previous shot, so a lower value means a faster auto fire cadence. Defaults to 100.

spam time (int): Manual fire recovery in milliseconds. While fire mode is 0, the weapon will not accept another fire press until spam time has elapsed since the previous press, so a lower value means a faster manual fire cadence. Recovery starts at the moment you press fire and runs in parallel with any swing speed wind-up: on a melee weapon with both fields set, the next press is allowed only once both timers have elapsed, so the effective fire cadence is whichever of spam time and swing speed is longer. Defaults to 100.

weight (int): How much the weapon slows the player down while drawn. Heavier weapons cost movement and reaction speed. Defaults to 1.

ammo type (string): Which character-wide reserve and damage bucket the weapon pulls from. Must be one of the sixteen recognized types: normal, gas, air, battery, powder, arrow, rocket, water, knife, needle, dart, ball, mana, fuel, rock, grenade. The default for non melee weapons is normal; for melee weapons it's none and the field is unused since melee weapons skip the ammo system entirely. Anything outside the recognized list (or a missing field on a non melee weapon) falls back to normal. The type drives both reload (player's reserve_<type> in kombat.sif refills loaded ammo) and damage (player's damage_<type> stacks on top of weapon damage and attack). Two weapons sharing the same type share the player's reserve and benefit from the same damage upgrade. Stripped from melee weapon files since they never read it.

ammo (double): npc weapons only. The per-weapon ammo reserve a non-player carrier draws from when reloading. Decreases by the loaded ammo count each time the reload completes, plays the empty clip when it hits zero. Player weapons ignore this field entirely — the player's reload pulls from the character-wide reserve_<ammo type> pool in kombat.sif instead. Stripped from all default weapon files since the per-weapon model is now npc-only and the parser falls back to the constructor default of 100 when missing.
loaded ammo (double): How many shots are currently in the magazine, ready to fire without reloading. Decreases by one per fire on non melee weapons, refilled from the active reserve when a reload completes (character-wide for the player, per-weapon for npcs). Defaults to 100.
max ammo (double): The magazine size, used as the cap on loaded ammo and as the target a reload fills back up to. The shop's weapon tab grows this per weapon — buying max ammo while an AR15 is drawn grows the AR15's clip but not the shotgun's. Defaults to 100.

unlock level (double): The minimum character level required to draw this weapon from the weapons menu. Locked weapons appear in the menu with an (Unlocked at level X) suffix and cannot be selected until the player levels up enough. Defaults to 1.

launch type (string): What the weapon fires when the trigger is pulled. The default is bullet, which sends out a regular bullet that travels along the wielder's facing axis. Setting launch type=projectile:<name> sends out the named projectile from builder/kombat/projectiles/<name> instead, with the weapon's damage, speed, and range carried over to the projectile's flight.

Projectiles fired by a wielder travel one way and disappear on first entity hit, giving rocket launchers and needle launchers a clean fire and forget feel. Setting launch type=bomb:<name> instead places the named bomb from builder/traps/bombs/<name> at the end of the weapon's range in your facing direction — facing right drops the bomb x range tiles east, facing forward drops it y range tiles north, facing up or down on a 3d map drops it z range tiles above or below, and a range of zero in the relevant axis lands the bomb at your own tile (drop a mine at your feet).
The launched bomb behaves like any normal bomb: it ticks until something walks onto its tile, then explodes for the weapon's damage value. Bullet speed is repurposed as the bomb's per-tick fall interval, so a slow-bullet weapon also lobs a slower-falling bomb. The field is ignored on melee weapons (melee=true) — a melee swing always resolves as a direct hit through the melee strike path, regardless of what launch type says, so there's no point setting this field on a melee weapon.

stun mode (int pair): Whether and how long the weapon's bullet or projectile freezes its target on hit, written as enabled:duration where enabled is 1 to turn the rider on and 0 to turn it off, and duration is the stun time in milliseconds. stun mode=1:500 makes a 500 millisecond stun on every successful hit. stun mode=0 (or 1:0, which is functionally the same) disables the rider entirely. The stun applies in both directions, so a human with a tazer rifle freezes the player and a player with the same weapon freezes a human, and is gated on damage actually going through, so a melee block or a full shield absorption ducks the stun the same way it ducks the hurt clip.

push x (int): How many tiles the hit shoves the target along the x axis on contact. The shove always reads as away from the attacker for melee, or along the bullet's x velocity for ranged, so a weapon with push x=5 swung from the west side of the target sends them five tiles east and the same weapon swung from the east side sends them five tiles west — the author writes a single magnitude and the direction is computed from the swing or the bullet at hit time. A negative number reverses the convention into a pull, so push x=-5 yanks the target toward the attacker (or back along the bullet's path) regardless of which side they started on, letting one field cover wind guns, magnet beams, knockback hammers, and tractor weapons. Defaults to 0, meaning no x push.
push y (int): The y axis equivalent of push x. Same sign-from-position and negative-as-pull semantics, with one extra wrinkle on 2d maps: a melee swing aimed up or down still drives push y instead of push z, since up and down are the y axis on a 2d map rather than a separate height axis. Defaults to 0, meaning no y push.
push z (int): The z (height) axis equivalent of push x. Same sign-from-position and negative-as-pull semantics. Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored. Defaults to 0, meaning no z push.

When the push runs into a wall or the map's edge before the full magnitude has been walked, every unwalked tile costs the target one extra damage per push value, so push x=10 that only manages three tiles before slamming into a wall leaves seven unwalked tiles and adds seventy damage (7 × 10) on top of the weapon's normal hit. This bonus damage bypasses defense entirely since it represents the physical slam, not the weapon's damage roll, and is reported in the kombat log on its own line (<enemy> was slammed into a wall for 70 damage or you were slammed into a wall for 70 damage) so you can read the swing's damage and the slam's damage separately. Doors, platforms, parked vehicles, and other entities do not block the push — only walls and the map boundary stop it, so a target shoved into an open door just keeps going through, while a wall pins them flush against the surface.

The push applies symmetrically across every hit path: your weapon shoves the npcs you hit, an npc's weapon shoves you on impact, and an npc's weapon shoves other npcs it hits during npc-on-npc combat. Same-tile melee (attacker and target on the same tile) falls back to the attacker's facing as the sign source, so a wind weapon swung at point blank still shoves the target away in the direction you're aimed instead of doing nothing.

health drain (int): How much health each fire or melee swing of the weapon costs the firer. Defaults to 0, meaning the weapon costs nothing to use. Negative values are clamped to 0 on read since regenerative weapons aren't a supported design.
Unlike stamina drain, the cost applies to every firer — a player wielding the weapon pays from their own health pool, and an armed human npc wielding the same weapon pays from its own health pool, so a desperate-but-powerful weapon authored at health drain=50 bleeds whoever's pulling the trigger. The drain runs once per successful fire (the empty-magazine click never costs health, since no shot leaves the weapon), and it never gates the action — health is allowed to fall all the way to zero. If the drain takes the firer to zero, they die the same way any other zero-health entity does: the player loses a life card and respawns at full health, or expires entirely if it was the last card, and an npc runs its normal death sequence. No pain or hurt clip plays for the self-drain itself — the cost is silent except for the weapon's own fire sound — since the firer is paying voluntarily rather than getting hit.

life drain (int): How many life cards each fire or melee swing of the weapon costs the firer. Defaults to 0, so the field is invisible on every stock weapon and only matters once an author sets a non-zero value. Negative values are clamped to 0 on read. This happends per drained card.
If the firer still has at least one card to spare beyond the current one, the cost plays the firer's life clip and refills them to full health — exactly the respawn pattern the /suicide command uses, so a life drain weapon feels like spending continues. On the firer's last card, the drain still consumes it but doesn't refill anything; instead it drops the firer to zero health and the regular death sequence kicks in (the player gets the you have died menu, an npc runs its normal permadeath). The cost applies to whoever's pulling the trigger, so a player wielding the weapon spends from their own card pool and an armed human npc wielding the same weapon spends from its own, letting authors build draws on the user's life weapons that are equally dangerous in either side's hands.

stamina drain (int): How much stamina each fire or melee swing of the weapon subtracts from the character's stamina pool. Defaults to 0, meaning the weapon costs nothing to use. Negative values are clamped to 0 on read since a regenerative weapon isn't a supported design; the regen handling is in the stamina pool itself, which slowly ticks back up to max while the value is below the cap. The drain runs once per successful fire (the empty-magazine click doesn't cost stamina, since no shot leaves the weapon), and it never gates the action — stamina is allowed to hit zero and a shot fired from an empty bar still goes off, you just have nothing left to push another button on until the pool regenerates. The drain only applies to weapons the player is wielding; armed humans and other npc carriers ignore the field entirely since they don't have a stamina pool of their own to drain.

reflection (bool): Whether the weapon supports the T key reflection toggle. When true, pressing T while the weapon is drawn enters reflection mode, where incoming bullets and projectiles have a chance to deflect off you instead of dealing damage. The weapon's folder must contain on, off, ref, and block clips for the toggle audio and deflection sound to play. Defaults to true for weapons in the melee category folder and false for weapons in any other folder, so the field is optional unless you want to give a non melee weapon reflective ability (e.g. a magic staff or a sci fi pistol with a built in deflector) or take reflection away from a specific melee weapon (e.g. a brittle dagger that can't bat bullets aside).

refchance (int or int:bool pair): The percent chance that an incoming attack gets deflected while the weapon is in reflection mode, with an optional cushion sub-value that controls how failed reflections behave. Written as refchance=N for a plain percent chance with no cushion, refchance=N:true to flag the weapon as cushioned (failed reflection rolls halve the damage that continues to your shield or your health, modeling a partial parry that softens the impact even when the deflection misses), or refchance=N:false (or omitted) to leave the cushion off so failed reflection rolls let the full damage through to whatever's next.

Only consulted when reflection=true and the wielder has the T key toggled on; weapons with reflection=false ignore this field entirely. The value is clamped to 0 through 100 on read, so a typo in the file can't push the rate outside the valid range. Defaults to 80 with cushion off, so a missed reflection roll lets the full bullet or melee damage through.
Every default weapon ships with refchance=N:false explicitly, making the no-cushion behavior the standard. Authors can opt back into the older partial-parry softening on a specific weapon by changing :false to :true, or build a brittle deflector at refchance=30, a perfect shield at refchance=100, or a roleplay only shield up stance at refchance=0 that plays the toggle audio without ever blocking anything.

Melee swings against indestructible walls.

A melee swing connects with indestructible walls (walls authored with destroyable=false) the same way it connects with any other valid target — the wall sits in the swing's range box and is picked by the same nearest-target rule as enemies and destructibles. The difference is that an indestructible wall doesn't take damage. Instead, the weapon plays its rico clip at the wall's position and the swing is consumed without any other target taking the hit.

Practically, this means an indestructible wall standing between you and an enemy will catch your swing first because the wall is closer to you than the enemy — the wall is in the way. To hit the enemy you have to position yourself so no indestructible wall is closer than the enemy on your facing side, or break a path through the destructible scenery first. The reco audio cue is your signal that the swing landed but did nothing useful, prompting you to reposition. Destructible walls keep their existing behavior of taking the hit and losing health, so the difference is purely about which walls are author-flagged indestructible.

Bullet ricochet against walls.

Bullets fired by non melee weapons ricochet off any wall they hit instead of vanishing on contact. The moment the bullet enters a wall's tile, the weapon plays its rico clip at the wall and the bullet's direction reverses — a bullet flying right that hits a wall now flies left, a bullet flying down that hits a wall now flies up, and so on. The bullet keeps its damage, its remaining range, and its full hit-detection, so it can come back and hit you, hit another entity nearby, or strike a different wall and bounce again. Unlike the melee case, the bullet does not deal direct damage to the wall on the bounce (only scadder splash damage does, and only against destructible walls). The bullet finally despawns when it has traveled more tiles from its spawn point than the weapon's x range, y range, or (on 3d maps) z range allows, so a long-range weapon fired into a tight room can rattle around for a while before petering out.

Practically, this means firing into a corridor with walls on both sides is dangerous: a missed shot can come straight back at you, especially with high-damage low-range weapons in cramped spaces. The same trick can also be useful — bouncing a shot around a corner to hit an enemy you can't see directly, or sweeping a small room with a bullet that ricochets through every entity inside before running out of range. Both behaviors apply equally whether the player or a human npc fired the bullet.

Specialized weapons.

Most weapons follow the standard ranged-or-melee model described above, but two weapon classes layer extra behavior on top by virtue of their folder name. Both are detected automatically — the engine looks at the leading characters of the weapon's folder name and applies the matching class behavior without any extra info-file field to set, so an author drops in a folder with the right name and the class semantics activate.

A cloner is any weapon whose folder name starts with the literal word clone (cloner, cloner_fast, clone_blue, and so on). Cloners behave as normal ranged weapons in every respect — they use damage, ranges, ammo, fire mode, reflection, scadder, and every other field the standard way, and shop upgrades for the cloner's ammo type apply normally. The added behavior is that when a cloner's bullet hits any of the fourteen cloneable entity types, a copy of that entity gets spawned alongside the normal damage, with the spawn position marching one tile closer to the player on each consecutive press until the clones pile on the player's own tile. See the cloning help topic for the full cloneable list, march behavior, reset rules, and authoring details.

A glider is any weapon whose folder name starts with the literal word glider (glider, glider2, glider_silent, and so on). Gliders are fundamentally different from normal weapons: drawing one turns it into a portable flight rig. Hold Ctrl to engage the engine and fly across the map at your normal movement cadence with gravity off, release to fall, re-press mid-fall to catch yourself. Combat is contact-based — flying onto a hittable entity's tile triggers a strike at your movement cadence. Most of the standard fields are forced or ignored on a glider (fire mode forced to auto, melee forced true, swing speed forced 0, weight forced 1, reflection and life drain forced off, ammo type forced to none, and bullet speed, repeat time, spam time, ammo lines, launch type, ranges, scadder, refchance, refcushion all ignored), so only damage, unlock level, stun mode, push, health drain, and stamina drain actually matter. See the gliding help topic for the engine model, the contact strike list, the seven required sound clips, and authoring details.

Weapons menu.

Pressing alt plus W (universal across 2d, topdown, and 3d maps) opens the weapons menu. The menu uses the audio forms tabbed layout: an all tab sits first across the top with every weapon from every category aggregated and sorted alphabetically, followed by one tab per weapon category (archery, artillery, explosive, melee, plus any custom categories you've authored under main/equipments/weapons/). The weapons inside the active tab sit in a list below.

Selecting a weapon from the all tab equips it from its actual source category — a hammer from the melee category remains a melee weapon when picked from all, and a sniper rifle from artillery remains artillery, so the sound previews and the equipped behavior match the weapon's authored category regardless of which tab you found it in.

Left and right arrows flip between tabs without leaving the menu, so switching from melee to artillery is one keypress instead of backing out to a separate category screen and picking again. Up and down arrows move through the weapons inside the active tab. Pressing enter on a focused weapon equips it and closes the menu, and pressing escape cancels and exits.

Locked weapons (those whose unlock level is higher than your current character level) appear in the list with an (Unlocked at level X) suffix and refuse to equip when you press enter on them, speaking the label so you know why nothing happened.

Sound previews play live on the focused weapon so you can audition a weapon's clips before equipping it. Pressing space plays the weapon's fire clip; control plus L plays the draw clip; control plus H plays the hit clip; control plus E plays the empty clip; control plus R plays the reload clip. Previews only fire while a weapon list is the focused control, so pressing space on a tab or on the okay or cancel button does the form's normal thing instead of triggering a preview.

The shields menu (alt plus S, also universal across all map modes) stays on the simpler list-based layout because shields aren't grouped into categories and there's nothing to tab between.
